args:
Despite having no chance to win, the prince
looks to challenge Xenos, which makes Emile
confront him about his lack of power. Persuaded
by his siblings, the prince faces reality and
crafts an evacuation plan for all of Grams.
A private home in Grams that we are\nrenting out as lodgings.
There are some yet asleep, but none\nwhose lives are in danger.
Had we taken another hit from Xenos,\nit would have been our end. We live only\nbecause Emile came to our rescue.
With the Dyrenell Army, right?\nI half-thought I'd dreamed that...
I know not what brought this mercy on,\nbut we should be grateful nonetheless.
And you, Phares? Are you all right?

As fate would have it, I appear to be
completely free from Xenos's will now.
Evidently the beast no longer needs my
body now that his true one has returned.
Perhaps due to the long time in which I\ngranted my body to Xenos, I appear to be\nsuffering none of dragonscale's ill effects.
Indeed. However, I stress that it is not\nwhat I could reasonably call a relief.
I was unable to stop Xenos, and permitted\nour foe's true return.
You alone don't bear responsibility for that.\nWe were all equally helpless.
Which is why we all need to join\nforces and stop Xenos together.
...Hmm? There's some kind of commotion\noutside. We'd better check it out.
Oh, it's not a new development.
Xenos's restoration has seen Grams\nblanketed in black mana.

Fiends have gone berserk as a result;
as we speak they're attacking the people,
destroying buildings, and generally
causing as much destruction as possible.
The Watch and the Dyrenell soldiers have\nmanaged to hold back the worst of the tide\nthus far, but...
Well, with the number of corrupted fiends\ngrowing by the hour. I question how long\nthey will be able to keep it up.
Meaning the citizens are in danger\nand we have no time to waste.
And just where do you think you're going\nin that condition?
I'm going to defeat Xenos and stop this\nblack mana at the source.
Your idiocy grows at a greater rate\nthan the enemies' numbers!
You can't do anything on your own,\nyou daft fool! It's pointless!
Why, you'd be lying cold in the ground now\nif not for me swooping in to save the day!
But all the people are in dan—
*sigh* Sometimes I wonder if you are truly\nthis witless, or just such a soft touch that\nit blinds you.
Everyone is in danger. Yes? What of it?\nThis is completely irrelevant!

Yes! It is! Completely, totally, one hundred
percent irrelevant! What, you think that
because some poor slob's in danger you
can accomplish what you couldn't before?
Does your world always come together\nso nice and neat as all that? Well, how \nlovely for you! I'm quite jealous, actually!
I won't just give up and do nothing\nwhile people suffer, Emile!

Oh, clap shut your pathetic gob already!
You can't do anything, yet you clamor on
and on as if your pretty words and empty
dreams might somehow make a difference!
Forget Xenos—you couldn't best a single\nelderly fiend on crutches as you are now,\nyou idiotic cretin!

You're probably too pure to realize this,
but there are some people who can't
survive this cruel world without giving up
on occasion or letting go of an ideal.
The world's not the kind of place where\nyou always get what you want so long as\nyou just ＂go for it＂ with a plucky attitude!
Is it not obvious? Give up! Tuck your ego\nbetween your legs and flee while you can!
No! I could never just abandon all these\npeople and just...just run away!
Fine then. Summon all your little friends\ninto a happy circle so you can talk about\nhow wonderful you all are AS YOU DIE!

You stand there claiming you would never
give up on anything, yet in the same
breath speak of how you're planning to
surrender your own life for no reason.
My dear Emile! You seem to have gained\na small bit of insight since last we met.\nI confess myself impressed.
And in that regard, I find myself in\nagreement with you.
Challenging a foe we know we cannot\ndefeat is not bravery, but madness.
A necessary quality in a leader is the\nability to carefully assess a situation—\nwhich includes the strength of the enemy.
Welcome back, you two.\nHow fares the city?
Xenos hasn't moved from the city center,\nand the black mana grows ever thicker.
It's merely a matter of time before the\nentire city is swallowed up.
If the black mana is still spreading,\nthere may yet be a chance.
If Xenos were to remake the world and fix\nthe future in place, they would have\ncomplete power over our life and death.
Which means there is no reason to attack\nus or the citizens of Grams.

And even if that were not the case,
we are but insects to Xenos—and one
does not go to any great lengths to
eliminate a mere pest.
Then how do you explain the fiends\ncurrently running loose in the city?
Likely Xenos's power is not yet complete.\nUntil it is fully restored, they won't want\nus interfering—hence the fiends.
Which means this is our chance to stop\nall of this before it can start!
...Except that I CAN'T stop Xenos or the\nblack mana. Not as I am now.
As the mana spreads and deepens, it will\nonly create more berserk fiends. There's\nno way we can possibly fight them all.
Just so. Attempting to battle Xenos or the\nfiends at present is a fool's errand.
And though our options are limited,\nwe still have some remaining to us.\nWe can still preserve possibility.
Xenos's power has not yet covered all of\nGrams; we must act before that happens.
I was mistaken. I see that now.\nMistaken about what I can do,\nand also what I SHOULD do.
Let us review the evacuation plan.
We will convey the children and elderly\naway via the Gran Fiore.
The injured and sick will be stabilized in\nGrams as best we can. Once that is done,\nwe'll spirit them away on a second trip.
How goes the medical care, Cleo?
Myself, Zethia, and Zena are spearheading\ncare for all who need it.
The number of people in need is great,\nbut I believe we'll see everyone by dawn.
Very good. Now then, any citizens who\nretain mobility will have to escape the\ncity on foot.
I'm not expecting any trouble from the\nnorth thanks to the agreement we signed\nafter the Satan incident.
But in the unlikely event something\ndoes happen, I will sort it out.
Still, South Grastaea is a considerable\ndistance away; we ask much of the people\nto walk all that way.
They have no choice. To remain here\nis to become feed for the fiends.
Exactly. Our priority must be reaching a\nlocation that the black mana's influence\nhas not yet reached.
If we accomplish that, we increase\nthe rate of survival.
We'll want to move at speed, but that\nwon't be easy while we're protecting\nso many people...
Enough dithering from you. You said you\nwere going to do it, did you not? If you've\nlost your nerve, then just stop already.
No, you're right. I'll give it all I have.\nThank you, Emile!
That was NOT an attempt to encourage\nyou, you daft addlepate!
We leave at dawn, everyone. Be ready.
